WEBVTT

00:00.824 --> 00:04.193
(narrator) Previously on
"The Making of the Mob: Chicago"...

00:04.279 --> 00:07.280
With Al Capone out of the picture...

00:07.449 --> 00:11.834
Frank Nitti, backed by Paul
Ricca and Tony Accardo,

00:11.953 --> 00:13.703
makes his first big move,

00:13.838 --> 00:17.674
shaking down Hollywood with
street thug Willie Bioff.

00:17.792 --> 00:19.008
It's all there.

00:19.127 --> 00:20.677
Always a pleasure.

00:20.795 --> 00:23.012
(narrator) But when Bioff gets busted...

00:23.131 --> 00:24.130
No names, no deal.

00:24.265 --> 00:27.183
Frank Nitti... and, uh, Paul Ricca.

00:27.302 --> 00:29.886
(narrator) ...Nitti is
unwilling to take the fall...

00:29.971 --> 00:31.020
(gunshot)

00:31.139 --> 00:34.140
...and Ricca is put behind bars,

00:34.225 --> 00:38.861
leaving the entire empire in
the hands of Tony Accardo.

00:40.315 --> 00:41.864
Looking to branch out,

00:41.983 --> 00:44.317
Accardo brings in up-and-coming gangster

00:44.486 --> 00:46.069
Sam Giancana...

00:46.154 --> 00:48.488
You ever hear of Eddie Jones?

00:48.656 --> 00:51.324
His racket's pullin'
in over a million a year.

00:51.409 --> 00:52.742
We can get in on it.

00:52.827 --> 00:54.911
I'll think about it.

00:55.046 --> 00:56.162
Uhh!

00:56.297 --> 00:57.417
What the hell are you doin'?

00:57.499 --> 00:58.664
I did what I had to.

00:58.750 --> 01:00.717
Nothin' gets done without my approval!

01:00.835 --> 01:03.886
(narrator) But, knowing the policy
racket could bring in millions,

01:04.004 --> 01:07.056
Accardo gives Giancana a second chance.

01:07.175 --> 01:08.758
I'm giving you something big here.

01:08.893 --> 01:10.343
Don't screw it up.

01:10.478 --> 01:11.344
(chuckles)

01:11.513 --> 01:14.430
♪ ♪

01:42.451 --> 01:46.584
- <font color="#D81D1D">Synced and corrected by VitoSilans</font> -
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.Addic7ed.com</font> --

01:49.217 --> 01:52.051
(traffic noise)

01:54.222 --> 01:56.556
Do yourself a favor.

01:56.641 --> 01:57.940
Start counting.

01:59.644 --> 02:01.778
(narrator) By the mid 1950s,

02:01.896 --> 02:05.114
Chicago mobsters Tony
Accardo and Paul Ricca,

02:05.233 --> 02:07.733
who's recently been
released from prison,

02:07.819 --> 02:09.735
have taken the reigns
of the criminal empire

02:09.821 --> 02:13.072
built by their mentor, Al Capone.

02:13.208 --> 02:17.743
(Robert Grant) Accardo and Paul Ricca
were very, very, very close friends,

02:17.879 --> 02:20.413
and they were willing to
share power, which, you know,

02:20.498 --> 02:22.248
at that level of... Of leadership,

02:22.417 --> 02:25.334
it's very hard to find
people willing to do that.

02:25.470 --> 02:26.636
♪ ♪

02:26.754 --> 02:28.304
(narrator) Thanks to Sam Giancana's

02:28.423 --> 02:30.590
takeover of the policy racket,

02:30.725 --> 02:33.759
the gangsters are now making millions.

02:33.845 --> 02:36.012
But, unlike their former boss,

02:36.147 --> 02:38.648
Accardo and Ricca realize they
have to be more discreet

02:38.766 --> 02:40.850
with their profits.

02:40.985 --> 02:42.705
(Frank Calabrese) The
big change that I seen

02:42.770 --> 02:46.022
and I was taught from the Al Capone days

02:46.157 --> 02:48.107
was the fact we had to go underground.

02:48.276 --> 02:51.077
We had to go far, far underground.

02:52.947 --> 02:55.364
♪ ♪

02:55.500 --> 02:57.867
(narrator) With so much money coming in,

02:57.952 --> 03:00.953
Accardo and Ricca know they
need a place to hide it.

03:02.624 --> 03:05.508
They find their answer in a growing city

03:05.627 --> 03:08.961
located in the middle of
America's Mojave desert,

03:09.097 --> 03:11.047
where gambling is now legal.

03:13.384 --> 03:15.685
Las Vegas, Nevada.

03:15.803 --> 03:16.802
♪ ♪

03:16.938 --> 03:18.115
(Michael Green) In the mid-'50s,

03:18.139 --> 03:19.972
Las Vegas is a boom town.

03:20.058 --> 03:22.225
But the rules haven't been written.

03:22.310 --> 03:24.393
It is, in a sense, a frontier town.

03:24.479 --> 03:25.862
There is room to maneuver.

03:25.980 --> 03:29.065
And Las Vegans are very conscious

03:29.200 --> 03:30.983
that they need industry.

03:31.069 --> 03:32.485
They need business.

03:32.570 --> 03:34.237
(narrator) Accardo and Ricca

03:34.322 --> 03:36.873
see Las Vegas as the holy grail,

03:36.991 --> 03:39.909
offering a way to
invest their illegal profits

03:40.078 --> 03:42.245
into a legitimate business.

03:42.380 --> 03:45.164
But they're not the
first ones with this idea.

03:47.135 --> 03:50.002
The New York Mafia is already there,

03:50.138 --> 03:53.556
led by criminal mastermind Meyer Lansky.

03:53.725 --> 03:55.258
(Meyer Lansky II) My grandfather,

03:55.343 --> 03:57.176
in the early days of Las Vegas,

03:57.345 --> 03:59.562
the first advantage he saw
is, everything was legal here

03:59.681 --> 04:01.230
that they were doing illegal.

04:01.349 --> 04:03.099
There was nothing to hide.

04:03.184 --> 04:06.269
And, uh, he saw it as
a money opportunity.

04:07.939 --> 04:10.356
(narrator) The New York
Mob runs the Flamingo,

04:10.491 --> 04:14.026
a luxury hotel and
casino founded by Bugsy Siegel,

04:14.162 --> 04:15.962
which is bringing in the
modern-day equivalent

04:16.029 --> 04:18.781
of $50 million a year.

04:18.866 --> 04:20.750
♪ ♪

04:24.839 --> 04:27.290
And now, the Chicago Mafia wants in.

04:35.183 --> 04:38.935
If we do this right...

04:39.053 --> 04:40.886
millions.

04:42.857 --> 04:44.273
I like the sound of that.

04:45.860 --> 04:48.311
We just have to be smart about it.

04:49.697 --> 04:52.565
Do you trust this Lansky guy?

04:52.700 --> 04:54.033
He'll understand.

04:55.403 --> 04:58.571
And if he doesn't...

04:58.706 --> 05:00.206
we can do it your way.

05:03.911 --> 05:06.746
♪ ♪

05:06.881 --> 05:08.748
(Michael) In a lot of
ways, the Chicago Outfit

05:08.833 --> 05:11.834
is as powerful as New York,
and it may be more powerful.

05:11.970 --> 05:13.252
("Ricca") Meyer.

05:13.388 --> 05:14.837
Paul.

05:14.973 --> 05:17.256
(Michael) When Luciano
forms the commission,

05:17.342 --> 05:19.342
he's got the five families of New York.

05:19.427 --> 05:20.926
He's got the Buffalo Mob.

05:21.095 --> 05:23.679
Well, the Chicago Outfit is
representing, basically,

05:23.765 --> 05:25.097
everything else.

05:25.233 --> 05:28.150
So they're taking in so much territory

05:28.236 --> 05:32.655
and so much action that
they have a big say.

05:34.942 --> 05:38.861
So... what can we do for you?

05:40.448 --> 05:42.948
We know Vegas has been good for you.

05:43.084 --> 05:44.404
We just want to make sure Chicago

05:44.502 --> 05:46.369
gets a piece of the action.

05:46.454 --> 05:48.704
(scoffs)

05:48.790 --> 05:50.706
So you're, uh...

05:50.842 --> 05:52.708
looking to muscle in on our rackets,

05:52.794 --> 05:55.544
and you're telling us... Why?

05:55.630 --> 05:57.463
As a courtesy?

05:57.598 --> 05:59.215
No.

05:59.300 --> 06:01.133
We're telling you because...

06:01.269 --> 06:03.302
we wanna go in on this together.

06:03.388 --> 06:04.804
We have enough partners.

06:04.972 --> 06:08.024
None with access to our kind of cash.

06:08.142 --> 06:10.643
Look...

06:10.812 --> 06:12.978
gentlemen, it wasn't
easy getting set up out here.

06:13.064 --> 06:14.563
(lighter flicking)

06:14.649 --> 06:17.033
Took a lot of time...

06:17.151 --> 06:18.984
and a lot of effort.

06:19.070 --> 06:20.653
We understand that.

06:20.788 --> 06:23.823
Which is why we wanna work together.

06:23.958 --> 06:26.742
We put money into your
casinos and cut you in on ours.

06:26.828 --> 06:30.329
Between your
connections and our finances,

06:30.498 --> 06:33.132
this'll be good for all of us.

06:40.508 --> 06:42.892
There's been a longstanding peace

06:43.010 --> 06:45.895
between New York and Chicago.

06:47.148 --> 06:49.065
Who am I to challenge it?

06:52.520 --> 06:53.402
To peace.

06:56.524 --> 06:57.656
And money.

06:58.860 --> 07:00.109
(glasses clinking)

07:00.194 --> 07:01.694
(narrator) With a partnership formed,

07:01.829 --> 07:04.196
the two criminal
organizations set up a system

07:04.365 --> 07:07.783
to take full advantage of Las Vegas.

07:07.869 --> 07:11.036
♪ ♪

07:11.172 --> 07:15.424
First, to pay for the
construction of new casinos,

07:15.593 --> 07:18.094
they secure legitimate
loans from local banks

07:18.212 --> 07:19.845
who don't ask a lot of questions.

07:22.967 --> 07:25.384
Then, when the
casinos are up and running,

07:25.553 --> 07:30.272
the mobsters use their legal
profits to pay off the loans.

07:30.391 --> 07:33.392
And finally, they begin funneling
their illegal money

07:33.528 --> 07:35.644
through the casinos.

07:35.780 --> 07:38.063
(Michael) Las Vegas became
a money laundering capital,

07:38.232 --> 07:41.200
and the Outfit, uh, took
full advantage of the opportunity.

07:42.904 --> 07:44.954
Gambling was a cash business.

07:45.072 --> 07:46.906
So who notices if you suddenly say,

07:47.041 --> 07:48.969
"Oh, here's a dollar going
here, and we'll move it over here."

07:48.993 --> 07:51.877
(birds tweeting)

07:53.131 --> 07:55.164
(narrator) As the operation grows,

07:55.249 --> 07:59.135
Accardo and Ricca know they
need someone on the ground,

07:59.253 --> 08:04.089
so Ricca suggests his
protégé, Sam Giancana.

08:04.175 --> 08:05.424
I'm just not sure about him.

08:07.478 --> 08:09.512
He's proved himself with
the policy wheel, no?

08:09.647 --> 08:11.096
He's made money.

08:11.232 --> 08:13.065
I've had to keep him on a short leash.

08:13.234 --> 08:16.519
How am I supposed to do
that when he's 2,000 miles away?

08:16.604 --> 08:18.854
Just give him a chance. He's earned it.

08:20.441 --> 08:22.691
Besides...

08:22.777 --> 08:24.577
at least he'll be 2,000 miles away.

08:24.695 --> 08:26.695
(chuckles softly)

08:26.781 --> 08:27.830
You have a point.

08:30.868 --> 08:33.785
♪ ♪

08:36.924 --> 08:39.174
(narrator) Despite his
personal reservations,

08:39.293 --> 08:43.345
Accardo knows Giancana's
success in the Chicago policy rackets

08:43.464 --> 08:47.016
makes him the perfect
choice to run the Vegas operation.

08:47.134 --> 08:48.017
Yes!

08:48.135 --> 08:49.134
(crowd cheering)

08:49.270 --> 08:50.636
Once again!

08:50.721 --> 08:52.137
(Michael) Giancana and Las Vegas

08:52.273 --> 08:54.139
go together very well.

08:54.225 --> 08:57.142
He was the kind of guy who
likes to hang out in casinos.

08:57.228 --> 08:58.948
He likes to be around
the good-looking women

08:58.980 --> 09:01.146
and the action.

09:01.282 --> 09:03.315
(narrator) Under Giancana's leadership,

09:03.451 --> 09:05.818
the Outfit's presence in Vegas explodes

09:05.953 --> 09:08.904
as gangsters from Chicago move west.

09:08.990 --> 09:11.991
(Meyer) Chicago Outfit became
very dominant here in Las Vegas.

09:12.126 --> 09:15.327
Quite a few people from
their Outfit planted here.

09:15.463 --> 09:18.163
Pit bosses, dealers, all kinds of,

09:18.299 --> 09:21.383
you know, on-the-ground, working
people, you might say.

09:21.502 --> 09:25.921
♪ ♪

09:33.648 --> 09:35.431
What are we working with here?

09:35.566 --> 09:38.400
(narrator) But one mobster
who's just arrived in Vegas

09:38.519 --> 09:40.269
catches Giancana's attention.

09:43.024 --> 09:46.692
The man who broke the
Mob's code of silence,

09:46.827 --> 09:49.361
sending Giancana's mentor to jail.

09:49.530 --> 09:51.363
♪ ♪

09:51.449 --> 09:55.117
And now, Giancana wants revenge.

10:10.933 --> 10:11.966
Well done.

10:12.135 --> 10:14.351
Thanks.

10:14.470 --> 10:16.053
Congratulations.

10:20.777 --> 10:23.811
(narrator) While making
his rounds in Vegas,

10:23.896 --> 10:26.030
Chicago gangster Sam Giancana

10:26.149 --> 10:28.732
spots a man from the Outfit's past.

10:30.453 --> 10:33.487
Willie Bioff, the
same man who ratted out

10:33.573 --> 10:36.540
Paul Ricca and Frank
Nitti ten years ago,

10:36.659 --> 10:39.493
and then disappeared.

10:39.662 --> 10:41.078
Willie Bioff does something

10:41.214 --> 10:43.714
that guys in the
Outfit don't traditionally do.

10:43.833 --> 10:45.082
He rolls.

10:45.218 --> 10:46.500
He testifies.

10:46.636 --> 10:48.502
And, under his assumed name,

10:48.588 --> 10:50.087
moves to Arizona,

10:50.173 --> 10:52.423
but can't stand to be out of the action.

10:52.558 --> 10:54.508
He comes up to Las Vegas.

10:54.594 --> 10:58.012
And that exposes him to organized crime.

10:58.147 --> 11:00.598
♪ ♪

11:03.019 --> 11:07.404
(phone ringing)

11:10.359 --> 11:11.358
Hello.

11:13.362 --> 11:14.945
Yeah, he's here.

11:21.370 --> 11:22.786
Yeah.

11:24.373 --> 11:25.539
Bioff?

11:25.625 --> 11:29.126
Yeah... with my own eyes.

11:29.212 --> 11:30.711
Of all the places in the world,

11:30.847 --> 11:33.881
he chooses our casinos
like nobody's watchin'.

11:34.050 --> 11:36.467
That prick needs to
be taken care of now.

11:36.602 --> 11:38.886
- Do you understand me?
- Yeah.

11:40.022 --> 11:41.889
I'll take care of it.

11:42.024 --> 11:45.476
♪ ♪

11:58.074 --> 12:00.908
1,319 days.

12:02.578 --> 12:05.329
That's how long I went without
seein' my family.

12:05.414 --> 12:08.082
Because that prick couldn't
keep his mouth shut.

12:11.087 --> 12:14.755
Paul... it's done.

12:14.840 --> 12:18.259
♪ ♪

12:27.687 --> 12:29.987
♪ ♪

12:41.367 --> 12:43.000
(keys jangle)

12:49.592 --> 12:52.509
♪ ♪

12:56.632 --> 12:59.516
(car stalls)

13:03.806 --> 13:05.306
(car stalling)

13:05.391 --> 13:07.641
(engine starts)

13:15.818 --> 13:18.702
♪ ♪

13:18.821 --> 13:21.872
(narrator) On November 4, 1955,

13:21.991 --> 13:24.742
Willie Bioff is killed by a car bomb,

13:24.827 --> 13:28.579
the ultimate payback for ratting
out his former partners.

13:28.714 --> 13:31.382
(Meyer) Tony Accardo and Paul Ricca,

13:31.500 --> 13:33.050
they were absolutely ruthless.

13:34.637 --> 13:36.920
They had both sides of
that ability needed

13:37.006 --> 13:40.341
for that type of a lifestyle.

13:40.426 --> 13:43.394
You had to be able to inflict
violence at some times,

13:43.512 --> 13:45.679
and you also have to be
able to use your logic.

13:51.520 --> 13:53.404
Now, basically, when they walk through,

13:53.522 --> 13:54.633
they're gonna be greeted immediately

13:54.657 --> 13:56.440
by lots of slot machines.

13:56.525 --> 13:57.970
("Ricca") This grand
ballroom will be the biggest

13:57.994 --> 14:00.611
grand ballrooms in any casino in Vegas.

14:00.746 --> 14:03.747
♪ ♪

14:03.866 --> 14:05.532
(narrator) Over the next two years,

14:05.668 --> 14:09.753
Chicago and New York launch an
ambitious expansion of Vegas,

14:09.872 --> 14:13.374
transforming four miles of Nevada desert

14:13.459 --> 14:17.127
into what will come to be
known as the Las Vegas Strip...

14:17.213 --> 14:19.213
♪ ♪

14:19.382 --> 14:21.382
...attracting nearly eight
million people a year,

14:21.517 --> 14:25.886
who pump over $200
million into the casinos.

14:25.971 --> 14:28.022
♪ ♪

14:29.558 --> 14:32.059
This is a beautiful ledger sheet.

14:32.228 --> 14:34.478
I want to frame it and
put it on my wall.

14:34.563 --> 14:35.979
(all chuckling)

14:36.065 --> 14:38.899
And it's just the beginning.

14:38.984 --> 14:40.317
To the future, gentlemen.

14:40.453 --> 14:41.452
To the future.

14:41.570 --> 14:43.037
To the future.

14:44.156 --> 14:46.657
♪ ♪

14:46.792 --> 14:48.575
(narrator) But Accardo
and Giancana see Vegas

14:48.711 --> 14:51.128
as more than a destination for gambling.

14:51.247 --> 14:53.964
♪ ♪

14:54.083 --> 14:56.917
The magic that really made it take off

14:57.002 --> 14:59.169
was combining the casinos

14:59.255 --> 15:01.922
with entertainment from famous stars

15:02.007 --> 15:04.341
like Frank Sinatra and Dean Martin.

15:04.427 --> 15:06.009
♪ ♪

15:08.647 --> 15:10.681
(narrator) Soon, the
allure of the Vegas strip

15:10.816 --> 15:13.350
begins attracting Hollywood's
biggest stars.

15:17.073 --> 15:18.772
And Sam Giancana takes advantage

15:18.858 --> 15:22.109
of all that the social
scene has to offer.

15:22.244 --> 15:24.194
(David Eisenbach) Sam
Giancana is a guy who

15:24.330 --> 15:26.997
liked to hang out with celebrities
like Frank Sinatra.

15:27.116 --> 15:29.700
Uh, he was a guy who liked to kind of

15:29.835 --> 15:34.338
rub shoulders with
celebrities and with the powers that be.

15:34.457 --> 15:37.124
♪ ♪

15:37.209 --> 15:39.626
(Frank Cullotta) The way Sam
was treated anywhere he went,

15:39.795 --> 15:43.714
they knew who he
was, and he was admired.

15:43.849 --> 15:46.016
If a movie star came
in the door with him,

15:46.135 --> 15:49.720
they would go to him before they
would go to the movie star.

15:49.805 --> 15:51.939
♪ ♪

15:57.062 --> 15:58.896
♪ ♪

16:00.649 --> 16:02.816
(narrator) As the money pours in,

16:02.952 --> 16:06.570
the Outfit comes up with
a way to make even more.

16:06.655 --> 16:09.239
It's known as the skim.

16:14.630 --> 16:18.332
(Meyer) The skim is money
that's taken off the tables

16:18.467 --> 16:20.834
before it can be recorded in a book

16:20.920 --> 16:24.087
or anything to do with being taxed.

16:29.512 --> 16:32.012
How it worked depended on the place.

16:32.097 --> 16:34.765
They rigged slot machines.

16:34.900 --> 16:36.183
They rigged the scales.

16:36.352 --> 16:37.568
You get in the counting room,

16:37.686 --> 16:39.570
and the money starts disappearing.

16:39.688 --> 16:41.772
♪ ♪

16:41.857 --> 16:43.440
Very nice.

16:47.329 --> 16:51.081
(William Forsythe) Once it went into
Vegas, they were bigger than anyone.

16:51.200 --> 16:53.040
You know, they were as
big as the oil business.

16:53.169 --> 16:55.085
♪ ♪

17:00.509 --> 17:03.260
(traffic noise)

17:05.513 --> 17:09.383
(door creaks)

17:09.551 --> 17:13.303
(narrator) But just as the Outfit's
Vegas operations are taking off,

17:13.388 --> 17:17.808
an incident over 2,500
miles away in New York City

17:17.893 --> 17:21.561
threatens to destroy everything
the Mob has built.

17:35.444 --> 17:38.362
(echoing heartbeat)

17:43.453 --> 17:46.120
(narrator) On May 2, 1957,

17:46.256 --> 17:50.208
New York Mob boss Frank
Costello is shot.

17:50.293 --> 17:53.127
But, miraculously, he survives.

17:57.434 --> 17:59.050
As the gangster recovers,

17:59.135 --> 18:01.886
the police make an unexpected discovery.

18:07.977 --> 18:09.694
(Meyer) The police
found a piece of paper

18:09.813 --> 18:11.696
that suggested that there was money

18:11.815 --> 18:14.982
coming out of the
Tropicana in Las Vegas.

18:15.118 --> 18:17.952
There was skimming going
on in the Tropicana Hotel.

18:19.873 --> 18:23.241
(narrator) News of the cops'
discovery spreads quickly,

18:23.326 --> 18:25.910
exposing the Mafia's ties to Las Vegas.

18:28.631 --> 18:32.333
This proved that an
organized crime figure

18:32.469 --> 18:34.585
was involved with the casinos.

18:34.671 --> 18:37.505
This was very embarrassing
for the local banks,

18:37.640 --> 18:40.508
who were lending money to these people.

18:40.643 --> 18:43.895
So, after that piece of paper was found,

18:44.013 --> 18:46.564
the local banks were
not going to lend money

18:46.683 --> 18:49.650
to buy and build and expand casinos.

18:54.157 --> 18:57.074
♪ ♪

19:01.581 --> 19:03.915
How are we supposed to
cover construction costs

19:04.033 --> 19:06.367
if we can't get a single loan?

19:06.452 --> 19:08.920
Not one. No bank'll go near us.

19:09.038 --> 19:11.289
The banks will come around.

19:12.959 --> 19:14.208
When?

19:14.344 --> 19:17.094
Soon... trust me.

19:20.049 --> 19:21.716
Until then...

19:21.885 --> 19:25.887
we just need to wait this
out until it resolves itself.

19:25.972 --> 19:28.723
We can't afford to wait.

19:30.193 --> 19:32.643
If we can't get the money from the bank,

19:32.779 --> 19:34.779
we need to get it from somewhere else.

19:34.898 --> 19:37.815
♪ ♪

19:41.871 --> 19:44.121
♪ ♪

19:47.911 --> 19:50.077
(narrator) To secure
the financing they need,

19:50.213 --> 19:53.464
Tony Accardo turns to
a source closer to home.

19:53.583 --> 19:56.751
I pledge to do
everything in my power to ensure...

19:56.886 --> 19:58.252
(narrator) A high-ranking officer

19:58.388 --> 20:00.555
in the country's largest labor union,

20:00.590 --> 20:01.973
the Teamsters...

20:02.091 --> 20:04.175
(applause)

20:04.260 --> 20:06.928
Jimmy Hoffa.

20:07.063 --> 20:09.383
I take a look around this
room and I can see a working man.

20:09.432 --> 20:10.648
Many working men!

20:10.767 --> 20:12.650
(cheering and applause)

20:12.769 --> 20:17.104
Nothing is more important to
me than our financial security.

20:17.273 --> 20:18.155
Nothing!

20:18.274 --> 20:19.407
(cheering)

20:22.612 --> 20:24.445
(narrator) Thanks to
the Outfit's influence,

20:24.614 --> 20:28.115
Hoffa is now the
president of the Teamsters union,

20:28.251 --> 20:31.118
and Accardo wants to call in a favor.

20:31.254 --> 20:33.371
That pension fund you started up.

20:36.092 --> 20:38.626
How much interest are
you charging on loans?

20:40.680 --> 20:43.464
About eight percent.

20:43.600 --> 20:47.602
But, for you, I could
get it down to six.

20:55.561 --> 20:56.978
Let's make it three.

20:59.699 --> 21:00.698
Three percent?

21:00.817 --> 21:03.317
Jimmy Hoffa was put in place

21:03.403 --> 21:06.320
and voted in from the Chicago Outfit.

21:06.489 --> 21:08.489
So, once he was in office,

21:08.625 --> 21:11.542
for that favor, they needed loans.

21:11.661 --> 21:12.960
Three percent?

21:16.165 --> 21:17.832
Is that a problem?

21:17.967 --> 21:19.667
No!

21:19.836 --> 21:21.085
No problem.

21:21.220 --> 21:23.054
Whatever you need.

21:23.172 --> 21:25.723
♪ ♪

21:28.227 --> 21:31.262
(Hillel) The Outfit took
hundreds of millions of dollars

21:31.347 --> 21:34.065
from the Teamsters' pension funds,

21:34.183 --> 21:37.234
which, in essence, was
Accardo's piggybank.

21:37.353 --> 21:39.904
And that money is really what financed

21:40.023 --> 21:42.907
the growth of Las Vegas.

21:48.998 --> 21:52.750
(narrator) But as the Outfit's
empire continues to grow,

21:52.869 --> 21:54.919
Accardo and co-boss Paul Ricca

21:55.038 --> 21:58.539
know they risk attracting
more attention.

21:58.708 --> 22:01.186
(Michael Madsen) Tony Accardo, he
wasn't interested in being flashy

22:01.210 --> 22:03.294
and being noticed,

22:03.379 --> 22:05.129
because then those... Those kind of guys

22:05.214 --> 22:07.131
were always the ones who went to prison.

22:07.216 --> 22:09.550
(narrator) To insulate themselves,

22:09.719 --> 22:13.220
the two Mob kingpins make
an unprecedented move

22:13.306 --> 22:15.556
by naming a new acting boss,

22:15.641 --> 22:17.892
a gangster who's made
millions for the Outfit

22:18.027 --> 22:20.311
and relishes the spotlight.

22:20.396 --> 22:22.697
Sam Giancana.

22:25.068 --> 22:28.819
You got big things comin', kid.

22:28.955 --> 22:31.238
And that's why we're talkin' to you.

22:31.407 --> 22:32.623
(flicks cigarette)

22:34.877 --> 22:36.827
We need somebody to run things.

22:38.414 --> 22:41.132
And you want that person to be me?

22:41.250 --> 22:43.417
Yes.

22:43.586 --> 22:45.886
But we need assurances you're
gonna stay in line.

22:48.558 --> 22:50.141
I will.

22:54.647 --> 22:55.930
(John Kass) Ricca and Accardo,

22:56.065 --> 22:58.816
their mentality was, no heat.

22:58.935 --> 23:02.153
No Valentine's massacre... none of that.

23:02.271 --> 23:05.489
So put a man named
Sam Giancana in charge,

23:05.608 --> 23:08.442
and they... They just sat quietly.

23:08.528 --> 23:11.028
And they dictated what happened

23:11.114 --> 23:14.198
and recede even
further in the background.

23:14.283 --> 23:16.951
Thank you.

23:17.086 --> 23:18.869
If you blow this for us...

23:19.005 --> 23:21.455
I know the consequences, Joe.

23:21.591 --> 23:22.790
Good.

23:22.875 --> 23:25.960
♪ ♪

23:26.095 --> 23:27.461
(narrator) In one move,

23:27.597 --> 23:29.764
Accardo and Ricca further
distance themselves

23:29.799 --> 23:32.183
from the public eye

23:32.301 --> 23:36.220
but retain the final
say in all big decisions.

23:36.305 --> 23:40.224
♪ ♪

23:40.359 --> 23:44.228
For Giancana, taking
day-to-day control of the Outfit

23:44.313 --> 23:47.314
is a lifelong dream.

23:47.450 --> 23:52.236
(Frank Cullotta) Sam Giancana
was, of course, power crazy.

23:52.371 --> 23:53.966
He grew up the hard
way. You know what I mean?

23:53.990 --> 23:56.657
In other words, he stole and
he robbed and all that,

23:56.793 --> 23:58.125
and then he became a big boss.

23:59.579 --> 24:01.495
(narrator) But what he doesn't realize

24:01.631 --> 24:03.747
is that he's about to become the target

24:03.883 --> 24:06.250
of an ambitious young attorney

24:06.419 --> 24:09.336
who he sees an opportunity
to make a name for himself

24:09.472 --> 24:12.923
by going after organized crime.

24:13.059 --> 24:14.675
Robert F. Kennedy.

24:27.945 --> 24:31.363
We need to get these guys tracked down.

24:31.499 --> 24:32.364
(man) Yes, sir.

24:32.500 --> 24:34.033
This is no joke, gentlemen.

24:34.202 --> 24:36.035
So if there's more resources
that you need,

24:36.120 --> 24:37.703
you come to me... You let me know.

24:37.788 --> 24:39.255
♪ ♪

24:39.373 --> 24:41.707
(narrator) After successfully managing

24:41.843 --> 24:44.376
his older brother John's
election to the US senate,

24:44.512 --> 24:46.045
Robert F. Kennedy,

24:46.180 --> 24:47.630
the seventh of nine children

24:47.715 --> 24:50.216
born to a growing political dynasty,

24:50.384 --> 24:52.885
is ready to make a name for himself.

24:53.020 --> 24:54.803
♪ ♪

24:54.939 --> 24:58.307
(David) I don't think Bobby
was bred to be a politician.

24:58.392 --> 25:01.861
The older brothers were the
future, uh, politicians.

25:02.029 --> 25:04.113
Bobby was the one who ran the campaigns.

25:04.232 --> 25:07.950
Bobby was the one who
kept everybody in line.

25:08.069 --> 25:10.369
And Bobby embraced that role.

25:12.456 --> 25:15.958
♪ ♪

25:16.127 --> 25:18.661
What rate of interest did
you charge on that loan?

25:18.746 --> 25:20.246
(man) I don't remember.

25:20.381 --> 25:22.414
(narrator) To further his career,

25:22.550 --> 25:24.083
Kennedy takes a position

25:24.218 --> 25:26.969
as the lead investigative
counsel to the US Senate,

25:27.088 --> 25:30.589
where he goes on a crusade
against corrupt labor unions,

25:30.725 --> 25:32.808
targeting leaders like Jimmy Hoffa.

25:32.927 --> 25:34.093
Mr. Hoffa,

25:34.228 --> 25:35.928
you have people in Detroit,

25:36.013 --> 25:39.098
at least 15, who have police records.

25:39.183 --> 25:41.433
One of those has 38 arrests

25:41.602 --> 25:44.320
and is a known associate of
Joe Accardo and Paul Ricca,

25:44.438 --> 25:47.606
two of Chicago's leading gangsters.

25:47.692 --> 25:50.276
(narrator) During the investigation,

25:50.444 --> 25:54.163
Kennedy uncovers a link
between Hoffa and organized crime.

25:55.950 --> 25:58.284
Realizing that the
corruption runs much deeper

25:58.419 --> 25:59.952
than the labor unions,

26:00.037 --> 26:02.955
Kennedy decides to
use the power of his panel

26:03.090 --> 26:05.624
to investigate the Mob.

26:05.760 --> 26:08.627
(David) Kennedy, who's looking
to make a name for himself,

26:08.796 --> 26:11.630
is gonna see, "Wait a second.
Here's an opportunity," right,

26:11.799 --> 26:15.301
"to... to use my righteous anger,"

26:15.436 --> 26:18.470
the black-and-white view of
the world, good versus evil,

26:18.606 --> 26:20.389
for his own political purposes.

26:20.474 --> 26:22.024
(narrator) One of the first men

26:22.143 --> 26:25.694
that Kennedy wants to
call to the stand...

26:25.813 --> 26:30.816
is the Outfit's day-to-day
boss, Sam Giancana.

26:30.901 --> 26:33.202
♪ ♪

26:35.239 --> 26:37.706
("Giancana") I feel like we
just pile up our money here!

26:37.825 --> 26:39.959
Again, again!

26:40.077 --> 26:42.745
♪ ♪

26:44.665 --> 26:46.143
(narrator) But when Giancana gets word

26:46.167 --> 26:48.584
that he's going to be subpoenaed,

26:48.669 --> 26:52.388
he does the unexpected and skips town.

26:52.506 --> 26:54.723
♪ ♪

27:00.264 --> 27:01.513
What?!

27:01.649 --> 27:03.932
Sounds good to me.

27:04.018 --> 27:07.403
Giancana played a lot of games,

27:07.521 --> 27:11.357
and among the games he
played was avoiding service

27:11.442 --> 27:13.075
for the subpoena that would bring him

27:13.194 --> 27:14.576
before the McClellan committee.

27:14.695 --> 27:16.996
♪ ♪

27:19.533 --> 27:21.116
(narrator) For almost a year,

27:21.285 --> 27:24.370
Giancana stays one
step ahead of the feds

27:24.505 --> 27:26.205
by hiding out in different cities

27:26.290 --> 27:28.874
and using a number of aliases.

27:29.010 --> 27:31.710
He was put in as the
operating boss of the Outfit,

27:31.846 --> 27:33.095
to mind the store,

27:33.214 --> 27:35.547
a multibillion-dollar enterprise.

27:35.716 --> 27:38.100
He's not minding the stores.

27:38.219 --> 27:40.552
♪ ♪

27:42.139 --> 27:44.973
(big band music playing)

27:47.395 --> 27:49.111
Why, hello there.

27:49.230 --> 27:51.230
You enjoying yourself?

27:51.365 --> 27:54.400
The goal is to bet as
high as you possibly can.

27:54.568 --> 27:55.818
♪ ♪

27:55.903 --> 27:57.569
♪ Let's have a moment ♪

27:57.738 --> 27:59.238
Sam Giancana?

27:59.323 --> 28:00.456
Yeah?

28:00.574 --> 28:01.790
You're a hard man to find.

28:01.909 --> 28:03.992
You've been served.

28:04.128 --> 28:08.464
♪ I haven't told you this won't take... ♪

28:08.582 --> 28:10.082
It's about time!

28:10.251 --> 28:12.000
♪ ♪

28:12.086 --> 28:13.502
♪ Maybe you're right ♪

28:13.587 --> 28:18.173
♪ ♪

28:23.931 --> 28:26.932
(narrator) Despite knowing
his bosses would disapprove,

28:27.068 --> 28:31.186
Giancana refuses to keep a low profile.

28:31.272 --> 28:34.823
So... what do you
intend to say to the committee?

28:36.277 --> 28:38.110
Well, I would like to
tell 'em to go to hell.

28:38.195 --> 28:40.279
(giggling)

28:40.414 --> 28:43.115
They couldn't catch me for a year.

28:43.250 --> 28:46.285
(whispering) That's very funny.

28:46.420 --> 28:47.953
So what do you think of Bobby Kennedy?

28:52.009 --> 28:54.960
I think Robert Kennedy has
no idea what he's in for.

28:59.350 --> 29:01.550
A number-one rule for any mobster

29:01.685 --> 29:03.185
is you don't want to be in the press.

29:03.304 --> 29:04.470
Where haven't I been...

29:04.555 --> 29:06.138
(David) It's... it's just bringing on

29:06.223 --> 29:08.640
way too much attention

29:08.809 --> 29:10.392
that the syndicate did not want.

29:10.528 --> 29:13.112
Anything he should be worried about?

29:14.815 --> 29:17.483
Guess we'll have to
wait and see, won't we?

29:17.618 --> 29:19.701
(giggling)

29:21.122 --> 29:25.324
♪ ♪

29:25.493 --> 29:29.378
♪ When I am down ♪

29:29.497 --> 29:30.496
(record crackling)

29:30.664 --> 29:34.249
♪ And feel uninspired ♪

29:34.385 --> 29:37.419
♪ ♪

29:37.505 --> 29:40.672
♪ If I fall ♪

29:40.808 --> 29:44.726
♪ I know I'll be fine ♪

29:44.845 --> 29:48.730
♪ ♪

29:48.849 --> 29:50.015
♪ That's why I'm here ♪

29:50.184 --> 29:51.567
Take a walk.

29:51.685 --> 29:52.768
♪ ♪

29:52.853 --> 29:55.521
♪ To say I love you ♪

29:55.656 --> 29:56.855
Now!

29:56.941 --> 29:59.858
♪ ♪

29:59.994 --> 30:01.577
♪ I'm so glad ♪

30:01.695 --> 30:03.612
(sighs)

30:03.697 --> 30:07.032
♪ You're mine ♪

30:07.168 --> 30:09.668
♪ ♪

30:19.513 --> 30:20.679
Damn it!

30:24.351 --> 30:25.968
(grunts)

30:27.521 --> 30:31.056
You're givin' interviews
to the "Tribune" now?

30:31.141 --> 30:33.942
Relax, I didn't say
anything I wasn't supposed to.

30:34.061 --> 30:35.777
Shut up! I know what I'm doing...

30:35.896 --> 30:38.146
Shut... up!

30:38.232 --> 30:40.399
(lighter flicks)

30:42.953 --> 30:44.953
When you go in front of the committee,

30:45.072 --> 30:50.075
you're gonna take the
fifth, every... single... time.

30:50.244 --> 30:51.210
You got it?

30:53.080 --> 30:54.129
Yeah.

30:57.218 --> 30:59.751
I got it.

30:59.887 --> 31:01.648
(Robert Lombardo) Accardo
never talked to the press.

31:01.672 --> 31:04.306
And it was frowned
upon, talking to the press.

31:04.425 --> 31:07.309
Why expose yourself? Why
expose what you're doing?

31:07.428 --> 31:09.811
And I think they learned
a lesson from Capone,

31:09.930 --> 31:13.982
because Capone, um, was more than
happy to talk to the press.

31:14.101 --> 31:16.151
Clean yourself up.

31:16.270 --> 31:17.819
You're a mess.

31:24.695 --> 31:26.245
Prick.

31:31.452 --> 31:34.086
♪ ♪

31:39.126 --> 31:41.843
(narrator) On June 9, 1959...

31:41.962 --> 31:44.012
Sam Giancana, the acting boss

31:44.181 --> 31:46.515
of the country's largest
criminal syndicate,

31:46.634 --> 31:49.468
arrives in Washington D.C.,

31:49.637 --> 31:51.970
ready to go head-to-head

31:52.056 --> 31:55.941
with one of the most feared
interrogators in the country.

32:08.566 --> 32:11.517
(narrator) After evading
federal agents for a year,

32:11.603 --> 32:14.320
Sam Giancana is about to testify

32:14.439 --> 32:17.273
in front of a congressional committee

32:17.408 --> 32:19.442
and come face to face
with the man determined

32:19.577 --> 32:22.612
to take down organized crime,

32:22.747 --> 32:24.330
Robert F. Kennedy.

32:29.287 --> 32:31.454
We ultimately
subpoenaed him in Las Vegas.

32:31.589 --> 32:32.505
That is correct.

32:32.624 --> 32:34.290
Following that Las Vegas visit,

32:34.425 --> 32:36.459
he returned to Chicago, where
he gave an interview

32:36.594 --> 32:39.045
to a reporter from the
"Chicago Tribune."

32:39.214 --> 32:43.633
("Kennedy") You may relate what
his opinion of the committee was.

32:43.768 --> 32:46.135
("Salinger") Ahem. He says,

32:46.304 --> 32:48.354
referring to the committee,

32:48.473 --> 32:51.724
"I would like to tell
them to all go to hell."

32:51.809 --> 32:54.477
Is that correct?

33:01.119 --> 33:02.919
I decline to answer because
I honestly believe

33:03.037 --> 33:05.288
my answer might tend to incriminate me.

33:09.544 --> 33:11.994
He also says, "They
couldn't catch me for a year.

33:12.130 --> 33:13.162
I like to hide."

33:13.298 --> 33:15.715
Is that correct, Mr. Giancana?

33:20.305 --> 33:22.171
I decline to answer because
I honestly believe

33:22.307 --> 33:24.724
my answer might tend to incriminate me.

33:26.344 --> 33:27.677
He was also quoted,

33:27.812 --> 33:30.062
when asked why he hadn't
served in any armed forces

33:30.181 --> 33:33.015
during World War II, as stating,

33:33.151 --> 33:35.434
"When I was called in front of the board,

33:35.520 --> 33:37.570
they asked me what kind of work I did.

33:37.689 --> 33:39.355
I told them I steal for a living.

33:39.490 --> 33:40.530
They thought I was crazy."

33:41.943 --> 33:45.027
"But I wasn't. I was telling the truth."

33:45.163 --> 33:47.196
(laughing)

33:47.282 --> 33:49.365
("Kennedy") The authorities in Chicago

33:49.534 --> 33:51.918
consider Mr. Giancana to
be the number-two man

33:52.036 --> 33:53.619
in the syndicate in the city.

33:53.705 --> 33:58.874
He and Mr. Tony Accardo,
number one and number two.

33:58.960 --> 34:01.544
Is that correct, Mr. Giancana?

34:01.679 --> 34:04.263
(whispering indistinctly)

34:06.551 --> 34:07.967
Mr. Giancana?

34:11.188 --> 34:12.989
I decline to answer because
I honestly believe

34:13.056 --> 34:14.806
my answer might tend to incriminate me.

34:14.891 --> 34:18.060
♪ ♪

34:18.196 --> 34:20.315
Would you tell us, if you had
opposition from anybody,

34:20.398 --> 34:22.898
that you have them dealt
with by stuffing them in a trunk?

34:24.202 --> 34:27.402
Is that what you do, Mr. Giancana?

34:27.538 --> 34:28.904
(chuckling) I decline to answer

34:29.040 --> 34:30.516
'cause I honestly believe
my answer might tend to...

34:30.541 --> 34:32.491
Would you tell us anything

34:32.577 --> 34:34.243
about any of your operations,

34:34.329 --> 34:35.389
or are you just gonna giggle

34:35.413 --> 34:37.913
every time I ask you a question?!

34:38.081 --> 34:42.635
I thought only little
girls giggled, Mr. Giancana.

34:42.754 --> 34:45.338
(Frank Cullotta) When these
guys, like Bobby Kennedy,

34:45.422 --> 34:47.005
and they got you in the crosshairs

34:47.091 --> 34:48.306
and they're questioning you,

34:48.426 --> 34:50.141
like these committees they got...

34:50.261 --> 34:53.646
Would you tell us anything about
any of your operations?

34:53.764 --> 34:55.542
(Frank Cullotta) ...and
they're gettin' cocky wit' ya,

34:55.565 --> 34:57.767
and you're just wishin' you
could come out of that chair

34:57.902 --> 34:59.902
and rip that son of a
bitch right off that pedestal

34:59.937 --> 35:01.437
that he's sittin' on over there.

35:01.606 --> 35:03.606
♪ ♪

35:06.944 --> 35:09.278
I decline to answer because
I honestly believe

35:09.364 --> 35:11.614
my answer might tend to incriminate me!

35:11.699 --> 35:12.999
(gavel pounds)

35:14.786 --> 35:17.119
(Chairman) Is there anything further?

35:17.255 --> 35:18.788
(scoffs)

35:20.008 --> 35:22.174
You may stand aside,

35:22.293 --> 35:25.127
subject to being recalled.

35:27.048 --> 35:30.800
Every battle that Bobby
Kennedy took up became personal.

35:30.968 --> 35:34.970
Everything was war for Bobby Kennedy.

35:35.106 --> 35:39.058
But Sam Giancana probably
looked at Bobby Kennedy

35:39.143 --> 35:42.144
as just that, a rich, snot-nosed kid

35:42.230 --> 35:45.314
whose dad's fortune was made illegally.

35:45.400 --> 35:47.700
♪ ♪

35:52.240 --> 35:53.456
(lighter flicks)

36:03.384 --> 36:05.835
Are you stupid?

36:05.920 --> 36:08.721
It's a publicity stunt.

36:08.840 --> 36:11.173
All Kennedy cares about is
gettin' his name in the papers.

36:11.309 --> 36:14.593
And how exactly
does laughin' in his face

36:14.679 --> 36:16.729
help things?

36:16.848 --> 36:19.181
It was funny.

36:19.350 --> 36:21.400
Don't you ever think?

36:23.488 --> 36:25.688
You're on very thin ice.

36:25.773 --> 36:26.917
And you're blowing this whole thing

36:26.941 --> 36:28.157
out of proportion.

36:30.194 --> 36:31.577
Get out of here.

36:36.033 --> 36:37.283
Now.

36:46.344 --> 36:48.544
(Frank Calabrese) Giancana
was too vocal,

36:48.679 --> 36:50.379
too out in the open.

36:50.515 --> 36:52.131
He wasn't underground enough.

36:52.266 --> 36:54.350
And I think it all went
to his head after a while.

37:00.057 --> 37:01.640
(narrator) To Tony Accardo,

37:01.776 --> 37:05.945
Sam Giancana has become a liability...

37:06.063 --> 37:09.398
who now risks bringing the
whole Chicago Mob down.

37:16.616 --> 37:19.033
(narrator) As Sam Giancana's
outrageous behavior

37:19.168 --> 37:21.285
becomes more of a
problem for the Outfit...

37:21.371 --> 37:23.421
I got it. Don't worry.

37:23.539 --> 37:25.206
(narrator) ...co-boss Paul Ricca

37:25.375 --> 37:28.259
knows he needs to rein his protégé in.

37:28.378 --> 37:31.879
Listen... this
business with you and Accardo...

37:31.965 --> 37:34.432
He's got a problem with me.

37:34.550 --> 37:36.884
I am living the life
you and I dreamed of.

37:37.020 --> 37:38.664
- Listen. Listen.
- And he's got a problem with that.

37:38.688 --> 37:40.499
Does he even know realize how
much money I'm bringin' in?

37:40.523 --> 37:42.034
- What's it gonna take to get respect?
- Listen, I don't...

37:42.058 --> 37:43.535
- I am runnin' the casinos.
- Listen...

37:43.559 --> 37:44.536
I am runnin' the policy...

37:44.560 --> 37:46.277
Listen!

37:46.396 --> 37:48.145
We got a good thing going on here.

37:48.231 --> 37:50.147
- We do.
- And the only way

37:50.233 --> 37:51.794
that I'm gonna be
able to keep it like that

37:51.818 --> 37:54.735
is if you stay in line.

37:54.871 --> 37:57.738
Let me take care of Accardo, all right?

37:57.874 --> 37:59.991
Go back to doin' what you do best.

38:00.126 --> 38:01.742
Make money.

38:01.878 --> 38:04.078
I don't wanna see no
more problems, okay?

38:04.213 --> 38:05.329
(exhales)

38:05.415 --> 38:06.580
Of course.

38:14.223 --> 38:17.508
♪ ♪

38:21.514 --> 38:25.599
(narrator) But in the midst of
Accardo and Giancana's growing feud,

38:25.768 --> 38:29.153
Paul Ricca is convicted of tax evasion

38:29.272 --> 38:31.522
and once again sent to prison.

38:33.609 --> 38:36.827
It's another blow to the Outfit,

38:36.946 --> 38:39.413
but the government is
just getting started.

38:43.836 --> 38:46.420
♪ ♪

38:49.125 --> 38:52.343
Who does that son of
a bitch think he is?

38:52.462 --> 38:55.513
This is the man that's
ordered the murder of dozens,

38:55.631 --> 38:57.264
maybe hundreds of men.

38:59.102 --> 39:01.469
(scoffs) And he just sits there,

39:01.637 --> 39:03.554
laughing, like it's some kind of a joke.

39:05.108 --> 39:07.558
Kennedy was willing to go after the Mob,

39:07.643 --> 39:11.529
uh, by any means
necessary, to use a phrase.

39:11.647 --> 39:15.566
With Bobby Kennedy,
everything seemed to be personal.

39:15.651 --> 39:16.984
What do you wanna do?

39:17.120 --> 39:20.404
I wanna hit 'em where it hurts most!

39:20.573 --> 39:22.656
The casinos.

39:22.792 --> 39:25.292
Get me the Nevada Gaming Commission.

39:30.666 --> 39:34.969
♪ ♪

39:35.088 --> 39:37.004
(crowd chattering)

39:39.475 --> 39:41.425
(chips clinking)

39:44.981 --> 39:46.147
Very nice.

39:48.267 --> 39:50.568
Mr. Giancana...

39:50.686 --> 39:52.603
could you please come with us?

39:54.690 --> 39:55.739
What's this about?

39:57.193 --> 39:58.442
Please.

39:58.528 --> 40:00.077
I'm not goin' anywhere.

40:02.365 --> 40:04.782
Kindly escort Mr. Giancana

40:04.917 --> 40:07.034
off the floor.

40:07.203 --> 40:09.203
Get your hands off me.

40:09.338 --> 40:11.956
I'm... Get your hands off of me!

40:12.041 --> 40:13.591
(grunting)

40:13.709 --> 40:17.595
♪ ♪

40:17.713 --> 40:19.880
(narrator) After Sam
Giancana makes a mockery

40:19.966 --> 40:22.850
of Robert F. Kennedy's hearings,

40:22.885 --> 40:24.718
the Nevada Gaming Control Board

40:24.804 --> 40:26.637
puts his name on a list of criminals

40:26.772 --> 40:29.273
who are barred from entering casinos.

40:29.392 --> 40:32.309
♪ ♪

40:38.484 --> 40:40.879
("Accardo") How the hell are
you going to run things in Vegas

40:40.903 --> 40:43.070
when you can't even step
foot inside a casino?

40:43.156 --> 40:44.321
It's temporary, okay?

40:44.407 --> 40:45.551
I already spoke to our lawyers.

40:45.575 --> 40:46.824
They said there's a good chance

40:46.909 --> 40:48.149
I can get my name off that list

40:48.244 --> 40:49.577
if I take it to court.

40:49.662 --> 40:51.412
Take it to court?

40:51.547 --> 40:52.963
Have you lost your mind?

40:53.082 --> 40:54.359
What do you suggest I do
then? Do you have any idea

40:54.383 --> 40:55.863
of the kind of press that will bring?

40:55.918 --> 40:57.751
What am I supposed to do?

40:57.837 --> 40:58.969
You fix it.

40:59.088 --> 41:01.138
I just told you how to fix it.

41:01.257 --> 41:03.307
Find another way.

41:03.426 --> 41:05.759
Otherwise...

41:05.845 --> 41:09.146
I'm gonna have to make some changes.

41:09.265 --> 41:11.398
(laughing)

41:13.019 --> 41:14.935
Okay.

41:15.071 --> 41:16.854
Good luck with that.

41:16.939 --> 41:19.607
♪ ♪

41:19.775 --> 41:21.942
(David) It's one thing to be

41:22.111 --> 41:24.111
a well-known gangster

41:24.197 --> 41:26.447
and to be hanging
out with Frank Sinatra.

41:27.950 --> 41:30.034
But now to be seen, you know,

41:30.119 --> 41:33.370
as this criminal,

41:33.456 --> 41:35.706
definitely makes life more difficult

41:35.875 --> 41:38.792
because it makes it harder
to buy off the politicians,

41:38.928 --> 41:41.128
it makes it harder to buy off the cops.

41:41.297 --> 41:44.131
Makes it harder to
basically run an operation

41:44.300 --> 41:47.968
if you have the... The
media glare like this.

41:48.054 --> 41:49.887
♪ ♪

41:49.972 --> 41:51.555
Everyone's replaceable.

41:53.726 --> 41:55.226
Everyone!

42:02.151 --> 42:06.904
(narrator) With Accardo and
Giancana's relationship deteriorating,

42:06.989 --> 42:10.658
and Paul Ricca in prison,

42:10.743 --> 42:12.326
the Chicago Outfit

42:12.411 --> 42:15.996
is on the verge of a total collapse.

42:16.165 --> 42:18.215
♪ ♪

